------>sudo docker run (if you are use this command at a time create a container and run the container
both are same use this ommand .)

running in your server.)
------> sudo docker run --name [Containername] [imagename]
------>sudo docker run --name web1 httpd
(This way to create the docker container and run the container at the same come command This way is
good for practice. example web1 is the container name and httpd is the image name).
First Command:
sudo docker run --name web1 https
sudo: Runs the command with superuser privileges.
docker run: This command creates and starts a new container.
--name web1: Names the container as web1.
https: This is the image from which the container is created. It seems you want to use an image named
https (you need to replace this with an actual image name unless "https" is a real image).
Second Command
sudo docker run -d --name web2 https
-d: Runs the container in detached mode (in the background).
--name web2: Names the container as web2.
https: Refers to the image you're using, just like in the first command.
Key Differences:
The second command uses the -d flag, which starts the container in detached mode. This means the
container will run in the background, and you won't see its output directly in the terminal.
The first command does not use the -d flag, so it runs in the foreground, and you'll see its output directly
in the terminal.
------> sudo docker exec -it tamil /bin/sh ->(This command is used to login our docker container)
